          "text": "Subagents in Cursor are specialized AI processes that the main agent (me) can launch to handle specific types of work in parallel or in isolation. Here's what each type does:\n\n## Available Subagent Types\n\n**`generalPurpose`**\nA versatile agent for complex research, multi-step investigations, and tasks that don't fit neatly into a specialized category. Good for exploring unfamiliar code or answering broad questions.\n\n**`explore`**\nOptimized for fast codebase exploration — finding files by pattern, searching for keywords, or answering structural questions like \"how do API endpoints work here?\" You can tune its thoroughness: quick, medium, or very thorough.\n\n**`shell`**\nA command execution specialist. Used for running bash commands, git operations, and other terminal tasks in isolation.\n\n**`browser-use`**\nAutomates a real browser — navigating pages, clicking elements, filling forms, and taking screenshots. Used for UI testing, verifying web app behavior, or any browser-based interaction.\n\n**`best-of-n-runner`**\nRuns a task in an isolated git worktree (its own branch and working directory). Used for running multiple parallel attempts at a solution and picking the best result, or for isolated experiments that shouldn't affect the main workspace.\n\n## Why They Matter\n\nThe main benefit is **parallelism and isolation**:\n- Multiple subagents can run concurrently, so independent tasks (e.g., exploring two different directories at once) finish faster.\n- Subagents don't share context with each other or the parent by default, which prevents one task from polluting another.\n- The parent agent coordinates results and synthesizes them into a final response to you.\n\nIn practice, when you ask me something like \"what is the structure of this codebase?\" I might launch an `explore` subagent rather than running search commands myself, because it's purpose-built to do that efficiently.",
