          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Yes, it's very deliberate. There are actually two distinct layers where tool use contents get excluded from the change history, for different reasons. Here's the breakdown:\n\n---\n\n## Layer 1: Transcript parsing skips `tool_result` items from user content\n\nWhen git-ai parses a raw Claude/Cursor transcript to build its in-memory `AiTranscript`, it iterates over user message content arrays. Any item with `\"type\": \"tool_result\"` is explicitly dropped:\n\n```225:246:git-ai/src/commands/checkpoint_agent/agent_presets.rs\n                        } else if let Some(content_array) =\n                            raw_entry[\"message\"][\"content\"].as_array()\n                        {\n                            // Handle user messages with content array\n                            for item in content_array {\n                                // Skip tool_result items - those are system-generated responses, not human input\n                                if item[\"type\"].as_str() == Some(\"tool_result\") {\n                                    continue;\n                                }\n                                // Handle text content blocks from actual user input\n                                if item[\"type\"].as_str() == Some(\"text\")\n                                    && let Some(text) = item[\"text\"].as_str()\n                                    && !text.trim().is_empty()\n                                {\n                                    transcript.add_message(Message::User {\n                                        text: text.to_string(),\n                                        timestamp: timestamp.clone(),\n                                        id: None,\n                                    });\n                                }\n                            }\n                        }\n```\n\nThe same pattern repeats verbatim for Cursor's variant of the transcript format at line 3003. `tool_result` represents the system-fed output of a tool call being returned to the model — it's not human input, so it's discarded at parse time entirely.\n\n`tool_use` items from assistant messages, however, *are* stored — but as `Message::ToolUse { .. }`, keeping them semantically distinct from human and assistant text.\n\n---\n\n## Layer 2: `extract_prompt_text_for_checkpoint` only looks at `Message::User`\n\nThis is the function that directly populates `ChangeHistoryEntry.prompt_text`:\n\n```575:601:git-ai/src/authorship/post_commit.rs\nfn extract_prompt_text_for_checkpoint(\n    messages: &[crate::authorship::transcript::Message],\n    prompt_id: Option<&str>,\n    checkpoint_ts: u64,\n) -> Option<String> {\n    use crate::authorship::transcript::Message;\n\n    if let Some(pid) = prompt_id {\n        if let Some(msg) = messages.iter().find(|m| {\n            matches!(m, Message::User { id, .. } if id.as_deref() == Some(pid))\n        }) {\n            return msg.text().cloned();\n        }\n    }\n\n    messages\n        .iter()\n        .filter(|m| matches!(m, Message::User { .. }))\n        .filter(|m| {\n            m.timestamp()\n                .and_then(|ts| chrono::DateTime::parse_from_rfc3339(ts).ok())\n                .map(|dt| dt.timestamp() as u64 <= checkpoint_ts)\n                .unwrap_or(true)\n        })\n        .last()\n        .and_then(|m| m.text().cloned())\n}\n```\n\nIt exclusively matches on `Message::User { .. }`. Even though `Message::ToolUse { .. }` entries exist in the transcript at this point, they are never touched. The function returns the last user text message at or before the checkpoint timestamp. The intent is clear: `prompt_text` in the change history is supposed to capture *what the human said*, not what the AI did with tools.\n\n---\n\n## The `ChangeHistoryEntry` struct itself confirms this scope\n\n```47:63:git-ai/src/authorship/authorship_log_serialization.rs\n/// One entry in the per-checkpoint change history stored in the authorship note\n#[derive(D